aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Description:
Size and Scope : With more than 950 beds, 100 nursing units (inpatient and outpatient), and over 4,000 nurses, Cleveland Clinic is one of the world's largest and busiest medical centers, serving patients from every state in the nation and from many countries around the world. Each year, more than 2 million outpatient visits are recorded, and approximately 65,000 surgical procedures are performed.
Diversity of Practice : The Cleveland Clinic offers a fast-paced environment where nurses learn, grow and remain personally and professionally challenged. Our nurses appreciate that they can customize and build their careers, within a variety of clinical specialties, to meet their needs and interests. Additionally, Cleveland Clinic nurses can practice in both urban and suburban settings including: hospital units, state-of-the-art operating rooms, sub acute rehabilitation center, outpatient clinics, family health centers, ambulatory surgery centers, and home care. The diversity of practice at Cleveland Clinic allows nurses countless ways to shape their careers. Endless opportunities and ongoing innovations make Cleveland Clinic the destination for nursing practice.
aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Name: The Cleaveland Clinic

aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Description: Cleveland Clinic, located in Cleveland, Ohio, is a not-for-profit, multispecialty academic medical center that integrates clinical and hospital care with research and education. Cleveland Clinic was founded in 1921 by four renowned physicians with a vision of providing outstanding patient care based upon the principles of cooperation, compassion and innovation. Today, Cleveland Clinic is one of the largest and most respected hospitals in the country.
aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Name: The Cleaveland Health Care Group

aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Description:
Cleveland Clinic Canada's extensive team of staff physicians and specialists are among the top names in the Canadian and international medical fields. They share a common goal that is both simple, yet revolutionary: to address all of your medical questions and provide you with the full attention you deserve. In the end, you can feel confident knowing you are receiving one of the highet levels of patient care available to prevent illness and improve your health and overall well-being. That's the Cleveland Clinic Canada way.
Cleveland Clinic Canada also provides a seamless referral resource to help patients access Cleveland Clinic facilities in Cleveland, Ohio and Weston, Florida. This service provides you the opportunity to explore the many advanced procedures and medical technologies available within Cleveland Clinic Canada's North American health network.
aWLIStructureHealthCareProvider.Name: The Quebec Cleaveland Clinic

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
As the nation's number one Heart Center, Cleveland Clinic offers nurses unique opportunities in every facet of cardiac care. In an environment where the extraordinary is commonplace, nurses collaborate as equal partners with physicians in developing strategies and interventions to improve patient care and outcomes as well as in evaluating new products and medications.
Facts and Figures: The Cleveland Clinic Heart Center is the nation's largest such center accommodating more than 200,000 patient visits and performing more than 8,000 surgical procedures each year. Our cardiac services include 14 in-patient units that are highly specialized in the areas of cardiothoracic, percutaneous interventions, medical cardiology, thoracic surgery and solid organ transplants.
All of the RN staff who work on the in-patient units are required to earn Advanced Cardiac Life Support certification within the first year of employment.
In addition to the in-patient units, you will find opportunities in our outpatient clinics in heart failure, cardiac rehab, preventive cardiology and special clinics such as the Marfan Center. Ambulatory services include the Cardiac Catherization Lab, Electrophysiology Lab, Ambulatory Electrophysiology, Syncope/Pacing Clinic, Preventive Cardiology, Ambulatory Cardiology and Cardiovascular Research.
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Health Center Hospital Units

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Mary Ann Coyne-Rosenberg Assistant Nurse Managers: Jeff Alvarez, Michelle Berndsen, Donielle Finding, Sandy Galvin, Judy Uzell
Number of Beds: 16
Skill Mix: RN-80%, CT-20%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Adults experiencing critical coronary problems: myocardial infarction, heart failure, valvular disorders, cardiac arrest, cardiogenic shock, dysrhymias * Aortic aneurysms * PTCas * Endovascular stents * Sepsis
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Coronary Intensive Care Unit (G20)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Katrina Hartig Assistant Nurse Managers:
Number of Beds: 14
Skill Mix: RN-80%, CT-20%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Patients with diseases of the aorta * Aortic aneurysms * Post-surgical vascular patients having undergone endovascular and/or open repair of the aorta or vascualr system
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Cardiovascular Intensive Care Unit (H21)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Mary Ann Coyne-Rosenberg Assistant Nurse Managers: Jeff Alvarez, Michelle Berndsen, donielle Finding, Sandy Galvin
Number of Beds: 8
Skill Mix: RN-80%, CT-20%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Adults experiencing heart failure * Patients experiencing cardiogenic shock, unstable dysrhythmias, primary pulmonry hypertension, cardiomyopathy, and sepsis * Post cardiac transplant rejection patients * Awaiting heart transplantation * Common therapies include: aggressive intravenous vasopressors, ACE inhibitors and diuretics, hemodynamic monitoring, ventilatory support, and intra-aortic balloon pumping
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Heart Failure Intensive Care Unit (H22)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Rosslyn VanDenBossche Assistant Nurse Managers: Karrie Foster, Kacey Neely, Kelly Stewart
Number of Beds: 24
Skill Mix: RN-85%, CT-15%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Preoperative and Postoperative adult cardiac surgical and thoracic surgical patients * Heart and lung transplant and ventricular assist device patients
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: CardioThoracic Intensive Care Unit (G50/G51)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Rosslyn VanDenBossche Assistant Nurse Managers: Linda Connell, Richard Haire, Cindy Mosier, Sharon Otero
Number of Beds: 21
Skill Mix: RN-90%, CT-10%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Post open heart surgery patient population * Surgeries include: Coronary artery bypass graft, cardiac valve repairs/replacements, thoracic aneurysm repairs * Patients are admitted directly from the operating room and are recovered, stabilized, weaned, and extubated * Typically, these two units admit 12 to 16 patients per day from the cardiac operating rooms
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: CardioThoracic Intensive Care Unit (G52/G53)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Rosslyn VanDenBossche Assistant Manager: Linda Connell, Oscar Dejelo, Melissa Solares
Number of Beds: 10
Skill Mix: RN-90%, CT-10%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* First time coronary artery bypass graft (CABG) and single valve surgery patients * Minimally invasive CABG and valve surgery patients * Myectomies * Maze procedures and off pump CABG patients to "fast track" through accelerated care pathway
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: CardioThoracic Intensive Care Unit (G54)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Pam Skocir Assistant Nurse Managers: Susan Hastings, Andrea Marek, Jackie Spence, Christine Zoretich
Number of Beds: 34
Skill Mix: RN-70%, PCNA 30%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Pre-op and post-op open heart surgery patients * Post myocardial infarction, post intervention, heart failure, and dysrhythmia management * Telemetry * Congestive heart failure and coronary artery disease * Electrophysiology patients: permanent pacemakers and ablations * Common procedures include thorancentesis and chest tube placement
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Postoperative CardioThoracic & Medical Cardiology Intermediate

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Clinical Nursing Director: Kelly Hancock
Nurse Manager: Debbie Brosovich Assistant Nurse Managers: Kelli Falbo, Becky Haney, Gary Kish, Molly Loy, Lydia Pitts, Lisa Rittwage
Number of Beds: 36
Skill Mix: RN-70%, PCNA-30%
Brief Description of Patient Population:
* Interventional or PCI patients * Angina or myocardial infarction * Congestive heart failure * Arrythmia patients needing medical therapy or EPS services such as temporary or permanent pacemakers and ICD insertion, ablation, cardioversion, etc. * Pre-op open heart surgery patients for coronary artery disease, aneurysms or faulty heart valves * Pulmonary hypertension with Flolan
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Medical Cardiac Step Down (G90)

aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
As the nation's number one Heart Center, Cleveland Clinic offers nurses unique opportunities in every facet of cardiac care. In an environment where the extraordinary is commonplace, nurses collaborate as equal partners with physicians in developing strategies and interventions to improve patient care and outcomes as well as in evaluating new products and medications.
Facts and Figures: The Cleveland Clinic Heart Center is the nation's largest such center accommodating more than 200,000 patient visits and performing more than 8,000 surgical procedures each year. Our cardiac services include 14 in-patient units that are highly specialized in the areas of cardiothoracic, percutaneous interventions, medical cardiology, thoracic surgery and solid organ transplants.
All of the RN staff who work on the in-patient units are required to earn Advanced Cardiac Life Support certification within the first year of employment.
In addition to the in-patient units, you will find opportunities in our outpatient clinics in heart failure, cardiac rehab, preventive cardiology and special clinics such as the Marfan Center. Ambulatory services include the Cardiac Catherization Lab, Electrophysiology Lab, Ambulatory Electrophysiology, Syncope/Pacing Clinic, Preventive Cardiology, Ambulatory Cardiology and Cardiovascular Research.

Brief description of the patient population: The Pacing and Electrophysiology Lab at the Cleveland Clinic Foundation is a five-procedure room suite designed to perform diagnostic, therapeutic and interventional electrophysiology based procedures. aWLIHCP_Unit.description:
Mailcode/Bldg location: S 60
Clinical Nursing Director: Nancy May
Nurse Manager: Mary Ann Jelenic, BSN, RN
Number of physicians in department: 5 full time; 4 part- time
Brief description of the patient population: We see patients of all different ages, generally elderly. A variety of arterial and venous conditions are evaluated and treated. Arterial conditions include peripheral arterial occlusive disease of the upper and lower extremities, carotid, renal and mesenteric vessels. Unique arterial diseases and disorders, such as fibromuscular dysplasia, Buerger's disease, entrapment syndromes, and thoracic outlet syndrome are also evaluated.
Venous disorders include deep and superficial thrombosis of the upper and lower extremities as well as intracerebral and intraabdominal veins. Hypercoagulable disorders, the antiphospholipid antibody syndrome ,and heparin induced thrombocytopenia are also addressed. Varicose veins, and chronic venous insufficiency are also seen.
Vasospastic disorders, such as Raynaud' s and erythromelalgia, as well as vascular components of the chronic regional pain syndrome are evaluated. We are asked to see patients with vasculitis.
We see a large population of lower extremity wounds in our ulcer clinic. Etiologies range from neurotrophic ulcers in the diabetic population, arterial, venous stasis ulcers to ulcers with an unusual etiology.
aWLIHCP_Unit.Name: Vascular Medicine (S60)
